Namasttay Shri Phil Ji and Everyone,

In Gurukulas in ancient times, a brahmachari(student) is given oral
instructions, and Vedas are committed to memory. There is a pattern of
reciting called jatha, ratha, ghanapatha etc which if you observe closely is
nothing but a  memorizing technique. The culture of writing was not
encouraged. So the question of British and Moghuls destroying the
Veda-Shaakhaas does not arise.

What can be understood is that, the number of Gurukulas and Brahmacharis
wishing to memorize Vedas were reducing day by day, with the advent of The
Age of Kali, and as such various Shaakhaas or disciplines got extinct as
none were left to either render or memorize them. Whatever written version
of Vedas you see now is may be due to a few people who have memorized it has
penned it down. However, Vedas are Shrutis(that which is heard) and not
Smritis(that which is written or remembered). So it does not make any point
to "read" a "written" Veda. Guru-upadesha or upanishata is always heard in
right hear, and never read or written.

As Vedas are very vast each Shaakha has its Rishi as head and a separate
department. This was for ease of administration. Obviously as different
Rishis come into picture, each Shaakha gets slightly modified to suit the
inclination of the Rishi. The Vedas were like open ended source code or
Wikipedia, where each Rishi can upgrade or modify it at relevant points
based on his tapasya and realizations. This gives a different taste to
Shaakha. However, the core fundamentals remains the same. So there is
nothing really worrisome that we have lost Shaakhas, as in my opinion, they
were incorporated for administrative ease. If you can master even one
Shaakha well, it is enough.

These are my opinions and one must not accept it until and unless it
convinces one's intellect, and when I give opinion, I may be wrong. Only
Shri Brahmarishi Gurudeva is blemishless and knows best. Thank You.

With Kind Regards,
Kannan
